\section*{Solution}

Put \(p(n)\) for the product of the digits of \(n\). We show that, for sufficiently large \(n\), a sequence starting below it cannot get past the "gap" from \(10_{\mathrm{n}}\) to \(10_{\mathrm{n}}+10_{\mathrm{n}-1}\). For suppose \(\mathrm{N}\) is the last member of the sequence below the gap. Then \(\mathrm{N}\) has at most \(\mathrm{n}\) digits, so \(\mathrm{p}(\mathrm{N}) \leq 9^{\mathrm{n}}\). But for sufficiently large \(n\) (in fact for \(\mathrm{n} \geq 21\) ) we have \(9^{\mathrm{n}}10^{\mathrm{n}}\) by assumption. Hence \(\mathrm{N}+\mathrm{p}(\mathrm{N})\) is sure to have second digit (from the left) zero.

So all further terms of the sequence are the same. But for any \(\mathrm{m}\) there is certainly a gap above \(\mathrm{m}\), and, as shown, the sequence will not be able to get beyond it. So it is bounded.

